Couple of things happening in that code. The first is:

```
PyObject_IsInstance(o1, (PyObject *)&WraptObjectProxy_Type)
```

which is using special knowledge in registrations of Python type objects about inheritance to work out that is the type we are interested in.

The second is:

```
!((WraptObjectProxyObject *)o1)->wrapped
```

where ``o1`` is a ``PyObject*``.

The type is defined as:

```
typedef struct {
    PyObject_HEAD

    PyObject *dict;
    PyObject *wrapped;
    PyObject *weakreflist;
} WraptObjectProxyObject;

PyTypeObject WraptObjectProxy_Type;

...

    if (PyType_Ready(&WraptObjectProxy_Type) < 0)
        return NULL;
```

The ``PyObject*`` is what ``PyObject_HEAD`` embeds at the start of the structure. So a point to ``PyObject*`` which satisfies the ``PyObject_IsInstance()`` check, would also be a ``WraptObjectProxyObject*``.

