You can accomplish this by instantiating [treq.client.HTTPClient](http://treq.readthedocs.io/en/release-17.8.0/api.html#module-treq.client) with a [twisted.web.client.Agent](https://twistedmatrix.com/documents/current/api/twisted.web.client.Agent.html) which has a `contextFactory` that doesn't do certificate validation. For example (untested):

```python
from treq.client import HTTPClient
from twisted.web.iweb import IPolicyForHTTPS
from twisted.web.client import BrowserLikePolicyForHTTPS
from twisted.internet.ssl import CertificateOptions
from twisted.internet import task, defer, ssl
from zope.interface import implementer

@implementer(IPolicyForHTTPS)
class WhitelistNoVerifyContextFactory(object):
    _browserPolicy = BrowserLikePolicyForHTTPS()

    def __init__(self, whitelist):
        self._whitelist = whitelist

    def creatorForNetloc(self, hostname, port):
        if (hostname, port) in self._whitelist:
            return ssl.CertificateOptions(verify=False)
        return self._browserPolicy.creatorForNetloc(hostname, port)

@defer.inlineCallbacks
def txmain(reactor):
    treq = HTTPClient(Agent(reactor, contextFactory=WhitelistNoVerifyContextFactory([(b'1.2.3.4', 443)]))
    response = yield treq.get('https://1.2.3.4/')

if __name__ == '__main_':
    task.react(txmain)
```

Admittedly this is not a terribly friendly API. There is more discussion of what we'd like to do at the `treq` level in #65. I hope this helps!

